{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} {{more footnotes|date=August 2010}} {{Infobox person | name =Cathleen Falsani | image= falsani1.jpg | caption = | birthname = |birth_date ={{birth date and age|1970|09|25}} |birth_place = [[Connecticut]] | age = | death_date = | death_place = | education = Graduate of [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]], master's degrees from [[Northwestern University]] and [[Garrett-Evangelical Theological Seminary]] | occupation =Journalist, author, columnist | alias = | status = | title = | family = | spouse = [[Maurice Possley]] | children = | relatives = | ethnicity = | religion = | salary = | networth = | credits = | agent = | URL =http://www.cathleenfalsani.com }} '''Cathleen Falsani''' (born September 25, 1970) is an American journalist and author. She specializes in the intersection of religion/spirituality/faith and culture, and has been a staff writer for the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'', ''[[Sojourners Magazine]]'', ''[[Religion News Service]]'', and the ''[[Orange County Register]]'' in Southern California. Falsani is the author of several non-fiction books on religious, spiritual, and cultural issues.
She was the 2005 Religion Writer of the Year, as awarded by the [[Religion Newswriters Association]], and has twice been a finalist for the Templeton Religion Reporter of the Year award.
==Education== Falsani graduated from [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]] in 1992, and holds master's degrees in journalism from the [[Medill School of Journalism]] at [[Northwestern University]], and in [[Theology|theological studies]] from [[Garrett-Evangelical Theological Seminary]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]].<ref>http://www.cathleenfalsani.com/god-girls-bio/</ref> She was born into a [[Roman Catholic]] family of Irish and Italian descent, but her parents left the Catholic church when she was 10 years old. With her younger brother, she was reared as an [[evangelical]] [[Protestant]] from grade school forward, largely in a [[Southern Baptist]] church in [[Fairfield, Connecticut]]. Falsani attended [[Christian Heritage School (Trumbull, Connecticut)|Christian Heritage School]], an evangelical Christian prep school in [[Trumbull, Connecticut]], graduating in 1988. She pursued undergraduate studies at [[Wheaton College (Illinois)|Wheaton College]] in Illinois, the evangelical Christian school that also counts the late Rev. [[Billy Graham]] among its alumni.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Falsani|first1=Cathleen|title=Sin Boldly: A Field Guide for Grace|date=2008|publisher=Zondervan|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=031027947X}}</ref>
==Career== Falsani is the author of ''[[The God Factor: Inside the Spiritual Lives of Public People]]'', a collection of 32 spiritual profiles of famous "culture shapers" including [[Bono]], [[Elie Wiesel]], [[Anne Rice]], [[Hakeem Olajuwon]]. Falsani's first book, it was published by [[Farrar, Straus & Giroux]] in 2006, launching [[Sarah Crichton Books]], a new imprint of the publisher. It was named among the best non-fiction books of 2006 by the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/2006/1128/p12s01-bogn.html|title=Best nonfiction 2006|last=Armstrong|first=Karen|date=November 28, 2006|website=Christian Science Monitor|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
Falsani joined the ''Chicago Sun-Times'' in September 2000, and served as the paper's religion reporter until 2007, continuing on as its religion columnist until Jan 13, 2010.<ref name=Rosenthal>{{cite news |last= Rosenthal |first= Phil |date= 2010-01-15 |url= http://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/towerticker/2010/01/brief-update-on-end-of-cathleen-falsanis-suntimes-religion-column.html |title= Brief update on end of Cathleen Falsani's Sun-Times religion column |newspaper= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate= 2010-09-08}}</ref> She wrote,'' [[Sin Boldly: A Field Guide For Grace]]'' (2008) a spiritual [[memoir]] and [[Travel literature|travelogue]] and ''[[The Dude Abides: The Gospel According to the Coen Brothers]]'' (2009), both published by [[Zondervan]].
Falsani is a correspondent and columnist for [[Religion News Service]]<ref>https://religionnews.com/author/cathleenfalsani/</ref> and a featured writer and correspondent for ''Sojourners''.<ref>https://sojo.net/biography/cathleen-falsani</ref> She also was Web Editor and Director of New Media for ''[[Sojourners]]'' from 2011 to 2012. Cathleen worked for ''The Orange County Register'' from 2013 to 2014.
===Interview with Obama on religion=== In March 2004, Falsani conducted an interview with [[Barack Obama]]. At the time of the interview, Obama was a [[state senator]] from Illinois and [[Democratic Party of Illinois|democratic]] nominee for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] in the [[United States Senate election in Illinois, 2004|2004 election]].<ref name=Obamafaith>{{cite web |last= Waldman |first= Steven |authorlink= Steven Waldman |date= 2008-11-11 |url= http://blog.beliefnet.com/stevenwaldman/2008/11/obamas-interview-with-cathleen.html |title= Obama's fascinating interview with Cathleen Falsani |website= blog.beliefnet.com |type= blog |publisher= [[Beliefnet]] |accessdate= 2010-09-08}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2014}} The interview focused on Obama's religious beliefs and spiritual predilections.<ref name=Obamafaith/>{{Unreliable source?|date=October 2014}}
==Personal== The granddaughter of Italian and Irish immigrants, Falsani was born and raised in [[Connecticut]]. Since 1997, Falsani has been married to Maurice Possley, the Pulitzer Prize-winning former ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' investigative reporter and New York Times bestselling author. The couple has a son adopted from [[Malawi]] in 2010, and they live in [[Laguna Beach, California]].
