[[File:Thanjavur - Brihadisvara Temple (54).jpg|thumb|[[Brihadeeswarar Temple]], [[Thanjavur]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]].]]
A '''Dhvaja sthambham''', '''kodi maram''' or '''kodi-k-kambam''' is a [[Flag#Flagpoles|flagstaff]] that usually features [[South India]]n [[Hindu temple]]s. 

Two other objects that are grouped together with this flagstaff, are the ''bali peetam'' (altar for offerings) and the vehicle ([[vahana]]) of the deity to which the temple is dedicated. Symbolically, these three objects are obstacles that protect the sanctuary of the temple from the impure and undevoted.<ref>[[Alf Hiltebeitel|Hiltebeitel, Alf]] (1991). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=diPh4qYtjPUC The Cult of Draupadi, Volume 2: On Hindu Ritual and the Goddess]''. University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0226340473}}. pp. 91-92.</ref>

