'''Ululudhvani''' is a tradition in [[Bengal]], [[Assam]] and [[Odisha]], where during [[Bengali Hindu wedding|wedding]]s and other [[List of festivals of West Bengal|festivals]] women produce a sound called 'Ululu'. It refers to festivity and prosperity. <ref>Arunoday Natvarlal Jani (1996). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=b9pGjXurxzIC Śrīharṣa]''. pp. 19-20.</ref><ref>A.K. Warder (2004). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=JF2zeNCIFh8C Indian Kavya literature: The Wheel of Time, Volume 7, Part 2]''. p. 301.</ref>
==Origin== This practice has origin in customs and rituals of Ancient Middle-Easterners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundstudiesblog.com/tag/ululation/|title=ululation - Sounding Out!|website=soundstudiesblog.com}}</ref> In [[Bengal]] this custom popularised by Arab Traders who traded in Ports of Bengal like [[Chittagong]].
